4.2 Data Exploration

"panel.lm" <- function(x, y, pch = par("pch"), col.lm = "red", ...) {
    ymin <- min(y)
    ymax <- max(y)
    xmin <- min(x)
    xmax <- max(x)
    ylim <- c(min(ymin, xmin), max(ymax, xmax))
    xlim <- ylim
    points(x, y, pch = pch, ylim = ylim, xlim = xlim, ...)
    ok <- is.finite(x) & is.finite(y)
    if (any(ok)) 
        abline(lm(y[ok] ~ x[ok]), col = col.lm, ...)
}
"panel.cor" <- function(x, y, digits = 2, prefix = "", cex.cor, ...) {
    usr <- par("usr")
    on.exit(par(usr))
    par(usr = c(0, 1, 0, 1))
    r <- cor(x, y, use = "pairwise")
    txt <- format(c(round(r, digits), 0.123456789), digits = digits)[1]
    txt <- paste(prefix, txt, sep = "")
    if (missing(cex.cor)) {
        cex <- 0.5/strwidth(txt)
    } else {
        cex <- cex.cor
    }
    text(0.5, 0.5, txt, cex = cex)
}
pairs(happy[5:10], lower.panel = panel.lm, upper.panel = panel.cor, cex.labels = 1.65)

6.5 Model Assumptions

6.5.1 Errors are normally distributed?

hist(mod6.1$residuals)

qqnorm(mod6.1$residuals)
qqline(mod6.1$residuals, col = "red")

shapiro.test(mod6.1$residuals)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  mod6.1$residuals
## W = 0.98012, p-value = 5.413e-07
### The histogram and qq plot look good, so i think it's ok even though it
### fails the shapiro test.

6.5.2 Errors are independent?

VIF(mod6.1)
## [1] 2.748686
dwtest(mod6.1)
## 
##  Durbin-Watson test
## 
## data:  mod6.1
## DW = 1.6674, p-value = 3.234e-05
## alternative hypothesis: true autocorrelation is greater than 0
### Errors are independent according to modc2 VIF score of 2.748686, but it
### fails the dw test. I don't think this is a problem.

6.5.3 Errors are homoscedastic?

plot(mod6.1$residuals)

bptest(mod6.1)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  mod6.1
## BP = 49.743, df = 3, p-value = 9.06e-11
### According to the bp test the errors are heteroscedastic , but i think they
### look ok in the plot.
